<td>
<p><strong>Brian Doyle</strong> is among the foremost purveyors of faith and family in the public sphere. He is the editor of <em>Portland</em>, <em>Newsweek's </em>two time selection as the Best University Magazine in America. He has written essays, non-fiction, "proems," and a novel. His writings have been published in <em>The</em> <em>Atlantic Monthly, Harper's, </em>and <em>The American Scholar </em>among others. His works have been honored with reprinting in <em>Best American Essays, Best American Science &amp; Nature Writing</em>, and <em>Best American Spiritual Writing</em>. His most recent book, <em>Grace Notes,</em> captures "the spiritual essence of everyday life." Doyle is happily married and has three children.</p>
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>
<p><strong>Tom and Louise Plummer</strong> taught at BYU for more than twenty years. Tom, also a noted essay writer, taught German, receiving his PhD from Harvard University.&nbsp;&nbsp; Louise, an English professor, is best known for her Young Adult fiction. Most notably <em>My Name is Sus5an Smith. The 5 is silent</em>. Her work has been recognized by the ALA, the Association of Mormon Letters, and the New York Public library, among others. For many years they team-taught a course on writing personal essays and memoirs. &nbsp;Louise fell in love with Tom while listening to his missionary homecoming talk. They have four boys.</p>
</td>
<td>
